        <td>1</td>
        <td><strong>Reliable Fault Detection in Depth Estimation for Robotic Picking Operations</strong><br>
        Efi Safikou (University of Central Florida)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster1')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster1" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Reliability is a key factor that constrains the adoption of agricultural robots, particularly for small and medium-sized farms. Such systems are prone to faults during field operations and require frequent maintenance, which makes them costly for farmers. For example, recent strawberry harvesting experiments indicate that a significant portion of harvesting failure cases can be attributed to an inaccurate height estimation. Therefore, the development of advanced fault detection tools is essential for ensuring the accuracy and reliability of sensed height information. This study introduces a physics-based, data-driven framework for designing an informative inferential sensor that achieves robust fault detection in noisy environments, thereby providing a cost-effective alternative to conventional depth-sensing hardware. The proposed approach leverages symbolic regression via genetic programming to derive mathematical expressions that accurately represent system parameters, even with limited training data. These expressions are optimized using the Ds-optimality criterion to enhance fault sensitivity beyond conventional (hard) sensors. The effectiveness of the proposed methodology is evaluated using the k-nearest neighbors (k-NN) classification to assess the fault detection accuracy of hardware sensor and to quantify the improvement achieved through the integration of the inferential sensor. 
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>2</td>
        <td><strong>Active Aeroelastic Membranes for Bat-Inspired Flight</strong><br>
        Stefania Konstantinidi (MIT)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster2')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster2" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Bat wings represent one of nature’s most refined aeroelastic structures. Unlike insect and bird wings, or current micro-air vehicles that rely on articulated rigid skeletons and passive membranes, bat flight is powered by soft, active and anisotropic membranes with embedded plagiopatagiales muscles. These muscles are actuated throughout the flap cycle to control the camber of the wing by varying the membrane stiffness, thus actively resisting aerodynamic billowing and modulating the lift.
          This work introduces an active, bio-inspired wing membrane using dielectric elastomer actuators (DEAs). By integrating rolled DEA fibers into a biomimetic anisotropic composite wing membrane, we mimic the biological elastin-collagen-muscle network of bat wings. The artificial plagiopatagiales allow the membrane to actively modulate its stiffness and shape under aerodynamic loads.
          Current prototypes demonstrate controlled camber modulation during gliding, with progression toward powered flapping flight. By shifting actuation from rigid joints directly into the aeroelastic surface, this approach bridges soft materials and aerodynamics, unlocking adaptive flight capabilities for next-generation bio-inspired aerial vehicles.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>3</td>
        <td><strong>Structural and Educational Determinants of Oral Healthcare Access in Greece: A Proposed Mixed-Methods Study</strong><br>
        Eleni Apazidou (Boston College)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster3')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster3" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          This research project examines the structural, educational, and socioeconomic factors shaping access to oral healthcare in Greece, with particular attention to how these barriers are understood and navigated by the Greek community. 

          Using a multifaceted approach, this study will combine policy analysis, review of dental education curricula, and qualitative interviews with practicing dentists and academic faculty. Fieldwork conducted in Athens, Thessaloniki, rural villages, and island communities will provide insight into systemic barriers such as cost, geographical accessibility, and preventative care interventions. Institutional engagement with leading dental schools will further examine how professional training addresses oral health inequities and prepares future practitioners.

          This research is informed by prior clinical exposure in Asprovalta, Greece, where early observations of access-related challenges shaped the foundation of this inquiry. By integrating firsthand experience with structured academic investigation and insight, this research aims to identify gaps between healthcare systems, education, and clinical implementation.

          Ultimately, this study seeks to contribute to a comprehensive understanding of oral healthcare inequities in Greece to inform future research, policy development, and community-based interventions. The findings will also support ongoing outreach efforts aimed at improving healthcare accessibility in underserved populations.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>4</td>
        <td><strong>Food Deserts and MASLD</strong><br>
        Sophia Mylonakis (Boston University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster4')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster4" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Metabolic dysfunction–associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) is an increasingly prevalent condition driven by metabolic risk factors and shaped by social and environmental determinants of health. This practicum used GIS-based spatial analysis and statistical modeling to examine the relationship between MASLD prevalence, food environments, and healthcare access in Houston–Harris County, Texas. Public health datasets were analyzed using Stata to assess associations between MASLD, food deserts, socioeconomic status, and racial/ethnic disparities. Geographic mapping was used to identify clusters of high MASLD burden overlapping with areas of food insecurity and limited access to care.

          The results show that MASLD is not evenly spread out; instead, it is more common in communities that don't get enough services, such as those with limited access to healthy food, lower incomes, and fewer healthcare options. Barriers in preventive care delivery, including gaps in primary care coordination and screening, further contribute to disease progression. The analysis highlights how fragmentation within the U.S. healthcare system and policy-level factors influence disparities in care access and outcomes.

          This work emphasizes the necessity of integrating spatial and social determinants into chronic disease prevention strategies.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>5</td>
        <td><strong>Off-Channel Communications: Effective Monitoring & Securities and Exchange Commission's Enforcement Priority</strong><br>
        Zoe Stella Mylonakis (Rutgers University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster5')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster5" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Under the prior administration of Chairman Gensler, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (the “SEC” or the “Commission”) set off-channel communications as an enforcement priority. Off-channel communications are messages sent through social media platforms, such as WhatsApp, outside a company's approved channels. The SEC has imposed fines on netted deals with banks, including Bank of America Corp. and Citigroup Inc., due to the banks' failure to keep records of electronic communications. However, under Chairman Atkins's leadership, off-channel communications are not a priority for examiners. Companies that violate off-channel communications policies face charges for books-and-records violations, breaches of supervisory duty, and monetary and reputational damage. Institutions can actively and effectively monitor off-channel communications by maintaining awareness of relevant rules, utilizing internal control systems, and exercising leadership. 

          At the same time, given the 40% rise in remote work, the Commission must preserve market and investor integrity. Digital transformation continues to raise privacy concerns about implementing record-keeping rules, especially because there are no clear guidelines on whether AI-driven communications should be captured by financial organizations. The SEC should make electronic surveillance one of its priorities for next year, given compliance requirements, technological advancements, and the need for data governance alignment.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>6</td>
        <td><strong>Uncertainty in Compound Decision Making with Applications to Ranking and Selection</strong><br>
        Andreas Petrou-Zeniou (MIT)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster6')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster6" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          The compound decision framework allows for decision making with many, noisy estimates. For example, researchers may seek to guide students to high value-added schools, or audit firms that are likely to engage in discriminatory hiring practices. Empirical Bayes (EB) methods allow researchers to approximate Bayes-optimal decision-making in this framework. However, because these methods rely on estimating a high-dimensional prior, they are subject to sampling uncertainty. This paper considers the problem of quantifying this sampling uncertainty in EB decision rules. To this end, I demonstrate that Bayes-optimal decisions depend on multiple posterior means, making controlling false discoveries difficult. I introduce a notion of uniform coverage of decision-relevant EB estimands that guards against these false discoveries. Leveraging a new connection between this notion of coverage and coverage in partially identified models, I provide a step-down approach to inference which provides tighter confidence sets relative to existing methods. To demonstrate the practical relevance of my framework, I apply my methods to the problem of differentiating between low and high-mobility neighborhoods. My methods uncover large gaps in mobility between census tracts, suggesting that policy-targeting on economic mobility is more credible than previously understood.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>7</td>
        <td><strong>Detection of Ultra-Massive Galaxies at High Redshifts</strong><br>
        Alexandros Mavroidis (Tufts University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#poster7')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="poster7" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Ultra Massive Galaxies (UMGs) when they are studied at high redshifts have perplexed modern Astrophysics and Cosmology, with their origin and characteristics defying conventional theoretical frameworks. Recent studies, using different spectroscopic approaches and optical and near-infrared instrumentation, suggest that massive galaxies begin forming much earlier in the universe’s history, where they accumulate most of their stellar mass.

          The KECK/MOSFIRE instrument has been used to spectroscopically confirm the existence of UMGs at redshifts z > 3, also suggesting rapid star formation followed by quenching. These observations have been further confirmed through Hubble Space Telescope (HST) data studying the growth and quenching pathways of UMGs at redshift slices of 3 < z < 4 from the MAGAZ3NE, COSMOS, and XMM-Newton surveys. Challenges posed by distant galaxies, such as faintness and obscuration, have been addressed through deeper NIR photometry. The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) has offered advanced sensitivity and NIR capabilities, exemplified by recent studies identifying candidate massive galaxies in the Early Universe, within the redshift range of 7.4 ≤ z ≤ 9.1 using NIRCam imaging. 

          Collectively, studies by the aforementioned telescopes indicate that advanced optical and near-infrared spectroscopy enable for stronger analyses of stellar populations and enhance investigations which defy current cosmological models of the properties of distant ultra massive galaxies.

        </div></td>
